  "prompt": "How is the ionization energy of hydrogen atom determined?",
  "response": "The ionization energy of a hydrogen atom is the minimum amount of energy required to remove its single electron from the ground state (the lowest energy level) completely, resulting in a free proton and a free electron. Determining this value involves both theoretical calculations based on quantum mechanics and experimental measurements. Here's a comprehensive overview of how the ionization energy of hydrogen is determined:\n\n## 1. **Theoretical Determination Using Quantum Mechanics**\n\n### a. **Schr\u00f6dinger Equation for Hydrogen**\nThe hydrogen atom, being the simplest atom with one electron and one proton, serves as an ideal system for applying quantum mechanics. The behavior of the electron in a hydrogen atom is described by the Schr\u00f6dinger equation:\n\n\\[\n\\hat{H} \\psi = E \\psi\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( \\hat{H} \\) is the Hamiltonian operator,\n- \\( \\psi \\) is the wavefunction of the electron,\n- \\( E \\) is the energy eigenvalue.\n\n### b. **Solution of the Schr\u00f6dinger Equation**\nSolving the Schr\u00f6dinger equation for the hydrogen atom yields quantized energy levels given by:\n\n\\[\nE_n = -\\frac{13.6\\, \\text{eV}}{n^2}\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( E_n \\) is the energy of the electron at principal quantum number \\( n \\),\n- \\( n \\) is a positive integer (1, 2, 3, ...).\n\n### c. **Ionization Energy Calculation**\nThe ionization energy corresponds to the energy required to move the electron from its ground state (\\( n = 1 \\)) to a point where it is free from the nucleus (\\( n \\rightarrow \\infty \\), where \\( E_\\infty = 0 \\)).\n\n\\[\n\\text{Ionization Energy} = E_\\infty - E_1 = 0 - \\left(-\\frac{13.6\\, \\text{eV}}{1^2}\\right) = 13.6\\, \\text{eV}\n\\]\n\nThus, theoretically, the ionization energy of a hydrogen atom in its ground state is **13.6 electron volts (eV)**.\n\n## 2. **Experimental Determination Using Spectroscopy**\n\n### a. **Spectral Lines and the Rydberg Formula**\nHydrogen exhibits distinct spectral lines corresponding to electron transitions between energy levels. The Rydberg formula relates the wavelengths (\\( \\lambda \\)) of these spectral lines to the principal quantum numbers of the initial (\\( n_i \\)) and final (\\( n_f \\)) states:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{\\lambda} = R_H \\left( \\frac{1}{n_f^2} - \\frac{1}{n_i^2} \\right)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\( R_H \\) is the Rydberg constant for hydrogen (\\( R_H \\approx 1.097 \\times 10^7 \\, \\text{m}^{-1} \\)).\n\n### b. **Determining Ionization Energy**\nThe ionization energy corresponds to the transition where the final state \\( n_f \\) approaches infinity (\\( n_f \\rightarrow \\infty \\)), as the electron is freed from the atom. Substituting \\( n_f = \\infty \\) into the Rydberg formula:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{\\lambda} = R_H \\left( 0 - \\frac{1}{n_i^2} \\right) = -\\frac{R_H}{n_i^2}\n\\]\n\nSolving for \\( \\lambda \\):\n\n\\[\n\\lambda = -\\frac{1}{R_H} n_i^2\n\\]\n\n### c. **Energy Calculation from Wavelength**\nThe energy (\\( E \\)) corresponding to the ionization process can be calculated using the relationship between energy and wavelength:\n\n\\[\nE = h c \\frac{1}{\\lambda}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( h \\) is Planck's constant (\\( h \\approx 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\, \\text{J}\\cdot\\text{s} \\)),\n- \\( c \\) is the speed of light in vacuum (\\( c \\approx 3.00 \\times 10^8 \\, \\text{m/s} \\)).\n\nSubstituting the value of \\( \\lambda \\) from above:\n\n\\[\nE = h c R_H \\cdot n_i^2 = 13.6\\, \\text{eV} \\quad \\text{(for } n_i = 1\\text{)}\n\\]\n\nThis experimental approach confirms the theoretical value of 13.6 eV for the ionization energy of hydrogen.\n\n## 3. **Summary**\n\n- **Theoretical Value:** Quantum mechanical calculations using the Schr\u00f6dinger equation yield an ionization energy of **13.6 eV** for the hydrogen atom in its ground state.\n  \n- **Experimental Confirmation:** Spectroscopic measurements of hydrogen's spectral lines, when analyzed using the Rydberg formula and energy-wavelength relationships, also confirm the ionization energy to be **13.6 eV**.\n\nBoth theoretical derivations and experimental observations converge on the same value, solidifying our understanding of the hydrogen atom's ionization energy.",
